      "This scenario engages section 35 of the Constitution Act, 1982, which recognizes and affirms existing Aboriginal and treaty rights. The Williams Treaties (1923) established certain harvesting rights for Anishinaabe and Mississauga communities, and these treaty rights are constitutionally protected under s.35. Section 25 of the Charter also operates here as a shield, ensuring that Charter rights cannot be used to diminish Aboriginal, treaty, or other rights belonging to Indigenous peoples.\n\nThe leading case is R v Sparrow (1990), which established the framework for analyzing infringements of s.35 rights. Under the Sparrow test, the First Nations must first establish a prima facie infringement of their treaty right to fish. The fishing regulations imposing seasonal limits and daily quotas clearly restrict their treaty right, satisfying this threshold. The burden then shifts to the Crown to justify the infringement. The Crown must demonstrate a valid legislative objective — conservation could qualify — and must show that the Crown's fiduciary duty toward Indigenous peoples was respected. This includes priority allocation to Indigenous fishing after conservation needs are met, minimal impairment of the treaty right, and meaningful consultation with affected communities.\n\nCritically, a counterargument exists that conservation is a legitimate objective. However, the Crown cannot simply assert conservation concerns without evidence, and the duty to consult requires genuine engagement with affected First Nations before imposing restrictions. The honour of the Crown demands that treaty rights be interpreted generously and ambiguities resolved in favour of Indigenous peoples. If Ontario failed to consult meaningfully or if the restrictions are more burdensome than necessary for conservation, the regulations would likely fail the Sparrow justification analysis and be struck down as an unjustified infringement of s.35 treaty rights.",
