      "This scenario closely mirrors Vriend v Alberta (1998), a landmark Supreme Court of Canada decision. The central issue is whether the omission of sexual orientation from a provincial human rights code violates s.15 of the Charter. Section 15(1) guarantees equality before and under the law and equal protection and benefit of the law without discrimination based on enumerated grounds and, crucially, analogous grounds. The Supreme Court in Egan v Canada (1995) confirmed that sexual orientation is an analogous ground under s.15.\n\nA preliminary question is whether the Charter applies at all, since the human rights code governs private relationships like employment. Under s.32 of the Charter, the Charter applies to government action. In Vriend, the Court held that the legislative decision to exclude sexual orientation from the human rights code was itself a form of government action — deliberate underinclusion by the legislature is as much a government act as any positive law. This established that legislative omissions can violate the Charter.\n\nThe discrimination analysis under s.15 would find that the exclusion of sexual orientation denies gay and lesbian individuals equal benefit of the law by depriving them of the human rights protections available to others. This constitutes substantive, not merely formal, inequality. The remedy in Vriend was 'reading in' — the Court read sexual orientation into the legislation as a protected ground rather than striking down the entire Act. This remedial approach preserved the human rights code while extending its protections.\n\nThe counterargument that legislatures alone should decide protected grounds fails because the Charter exists precisely to protect minorities from majoritarian preferences. Courts have the constitutional duty to ensure that legislative choices comply with Charter guarantees, and reading in was the minimally intrusive remedy that respected both legislative purpose and constitutional rights.",
