    modelAnswer:
      "Section 11(b) of the Charter guarantees the right to be tried within a reasonable time. The current framework is established by R v Jordan (2016), which replaced the older, more flexible Morin framework with a presumptive ceiling approach. For cases in superior court, the presumptive ceiling is 30 months from the laying of charges to the actual or anticipated end of trial. For provincial court cases, it is 18 months. If the total delay exceeds the ceiling — after subtracting defence delay — the delay is presumptively unreasonable, and the Crown bears the burden of rebutting that presumption by showing exceptional circumstances.\n\nIn David's case, the total delay is 34 months in superior court, exceeding the 30-month ceiling by 4 months. The critical question is how much delay is attributable to the defence. The change in defence counsel is likely defence delay and would be subtracted from the total. If, for example, the change in counsel caused 3 months of delay, the net delay would be 31 months — still above the ceiling. Crown disclosure delays are not defence delay and count against the Crown, as the Crown has a constitutional obligation to make timely disclosure.\n\nWith the net delay exceeding 30 months, the Crown must demonstrate exceptional circumstances — discrete events or particularly complex cases that were reasonably unavoidable. Generic court scheduling issues constitute institutional delay, which Jordan was specifically designed to address; they are not exceptional circumstances. Case complexity is a potential argument, but the Crown must show the complexity was genuinely exceptional, not merely that the case involved significant evidence. Drug trafficking cases, while serious, are not inherently exceptional.\n\nThe counterargument is that rigid ceilings may force courts to stay serious charges, letting potentially dangerous offenders go free. However, Jordan was explicit that the justice system must adapt its practices to respect the constitutional right to timely trial. The likely outcome is a stay of proceedings under s.24(1) of the Charter.",
